Highlights from the first day of National Team Trials.

Feeling oddly relieved after a less than ideal performance at Team Trials. Don’t get me wrong, the World Cup circuit has been an extraordinary opportunity these last two years, but leading up to Team Trials this year, I was struggling to articulate a deeper “why” for why I wanted/needed to do all of the World Cups. I will be back stronger and smarter next year but I’m excited to have a bit more time and energy to devote towards other goals (school, coaching, outdoor projects, creative work, etc) in the meantime. Cheers to everyone who makes these events possible and the stacked crew of athletes who made the team this year!

Feeling an unfamiliar set of emotions after a revealing round in Seoul. This was the first round of climbing in recent memory that I felt beat me mentally. I didn’t stay true to my training and ultimately found myself battling my own headspace to stay present and confident. My immediate take away is that I took my strength/experience for granted and went into the round with burdensome expectations rather than useful intentions. I’m frustrated because I’ve learned this lesson before and have practiced making the adjustments but evidently, it needed to be reinforced. No matter your physical condition, I felt in some of the best shape of my life for this comp, the role of mindfulness is always profound.

Comp 📸: @vladek_zumr

The science and real-world application of flow has been a topic of fascination for a long time now. Starting with the book “The Rise of Superman” I became obsessed with understanding more about this elusive state and learning about how to integrate research-proven tools to help find flow more consistently. I’m very grateful to have had the opportunity to work with such an experienced team of filmmakers and producers to create a film unlike any other climbing related project I’ve been a part of. For the full film, check out the @lasportiva youtube page. I know the film is somewhat vague in terms of actionable practices so to help share some of my favorite flow-related material, I added a page to my website (link in bio) that has links to my favorite flow-related books, podcasts, scientific articles, and videos.  

I also just uploaded a behind the scene video about the filming that went into “The Flow State” film to my own youtube (Ross-Fulkerson) 

Thanks again to everyone who helped make this project possible!

Nationals, nearly really good… 

My primary goal for this event was to follow through with the mental and physical pre-comp & warm-up exercises that put me in a position to succeed. Routines like meditation, stretching, visualization, & keeping a performance journal. For ropes, this worked well, and on average, I felt more present and confident than I ever have in prior comps. After an incredibly fun and flowy finals route, I finished in 3rd. While it’s had to complain about a podium finish, I know I had more to give and it’s made me hungry to pursue more sport climbing goals. For the boulder semifinals, despite being in a solid headspace, I got caught up looking for the most efficient/cleanest solution to problems, when in reality I just needed to get them done. I keep coming back to the idea that I need to do a better job at deliberately adapting my process of problem-solving to the specific style of climbs I’ll encounter at that comp. All and all, I'm psyched about the gains I made in sport and looking forward to the next month of hectic travel for outdoor climbs, cash comps, and clinics with @mind.to.motion 

Full recap/reflection video along with some boulders from Swan Falls on my YouTube 🤙
